Just get familiar with anatomy in general. Pretty much all mammals have mostly the same parts, just in different configurations. Humans and cows have the same number of teeth, for instance. It's just that the cow only has incisors and molars. All 8 incisors are on the bottom jaw, and three pairs of molars top and bottom on either side. They have no top front teeth, just a thick pad of skin. They're so specialized towards eating grass that it's pretty much all they can comfortably eat.

Play around with the basic structures, shifting them around but making sure they're all there or at least mechanically sound. If you keep things looking biological they'll be more believable.

For those of you struggling with lucid dreams, I found a way to hack them a bit to get higher rates of success.

First make a recording of yourself saying "this is a dream, if you can hear this recording you are dreaming, make a reality check" and some similar stuff. Follow that by a 5 minute silence in the recording.

Then make a file of 20 minutes of silence.

Now make a playlist where you have the 20 minute silence file (or however long it takes you to get to sleep) followed by like 30 repetitions of your dreamhack recording file.

Listen to this as you go to sleep and you should hear it in the dream and catch on that you're dreaming. It has to be loud enough to penetrate the dream but not too loud to wake you up all the way.
